Eirik, the culprit is, that the stylesheet you set on an HTMLEditorKit is shared by all instances. The setter codes reads like this:

```java
    public void setStyleSheet(StyleSheet s) {
        if (s == null) {
            AppContext.getAppContext().remove(DEFAULT_STYLES_KEY);
        } else {
            AppContext.getAppContext().put(DEFAULT_STYLES_KEY, s);
        }
    }
```

From the outside it might look as if you are setting an instance attribute, it is for all intents and purposes a global state you are changing. So yes the existing manipulation of the state is IMHO dangerous. Your change is in line with the established code paths - you just made me look at it :-)

You could check if you can apply the css changes to the document stylesheet and not the global css one.

I'm a bit fuzzy how `setFont` and the `addRule` interact, but I tested your changes and they work. So I would be willing to merge the changeset as is and postpone a complete rework for later.

That explains it :(  I never caught that scenario :(  Okay my bad I'll work on this during the week.

Thanks for spotting this @Chris2011 

@sdedic - Yeah I noticed I was making that recursive by mistake last night, I alreadyremoved that line, just haven't committed it as I was hoping to go through the other comments

@geertjanw it should be without the `.html` suffix IMO.  I'm also not sure about putting it under misc - though having one subsection used for all things linked to from the IDE might be a good idea, and possibly version specific so that update centre links can be there too.  And all links should be `https` unless we have a very valid reason for them not to be - the website doesn't currently enforce that but probably should.

So, my vote would probably be something like `https://netbeans.apache.org/nb90/issues`

I pinged @vieiro earlier for his thoughts on this - he's looked a lot more at the `.htaccess` and update centre config on the site.
